liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: There are 100,000 Israeli reserve troops gathered in southern Israel "preparing to execute the task that the Israeli Government has designated the Israeli military to do", according to IDF spokesperson Jonathan Conricus. In a video posted to the IDF X account, Conricus said: "Our job is to make sure that at the end of this war, Hamas will no longer have any military capability to threatens Israelis civilians with." "And in addition to that, we are to also make sure Hamas will not be able to govern the Gaza Strip." Yesterday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said his security cabinet had made the decision to destroy Hamas’s ability to govern in a way that posed a threat to Israeli civilians.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The United Nations says the number of displaced Gazans has risen to more than 123,000 as a result of the fighting between the Israeli military and Hamas following the militant group’s attack across the border. As of late Sunday (local time), retaliatory Israeli airstrikes had destroyed 159 housing units across Gaza and severely damaged 1,210 others, according to the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs. The UN agency for Palestinian refugees said a school sheltering more than 225 people took a direct hit. It did not say where the fire came from. AP

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you can't make it to a polling place this Saturday, October 14, then don't fret - the AEC has confirmed that early voting places will be open until Friday. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A prominent Yes campaigner says if the referendum fails, it will be a "travesty for the country". On Saturday, Australians will be asked whether they support enshrining the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Voice in the constitution. The majority of polls suggest the referendum will not be successful. Noel Pearson, who is one of the architects of the Uluru Statement of the Heart, which put forward the Voice to Parliament, says that outcome would be disappointing. "This is a moral choice for the country, not just a question of constitutional law," he told AM. "The choice we have is not equivalent - Yes and No are not equivalent choices. "Yes is of a different quality to No. No would be a travesty for the country." You can listen to the full interview on AM with Sabra Lane by taping the link below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Jake Evans Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has rebuffed a former Labor strategist's view the Yes campaign has been defeated. After one poll suggested support had fallen another 2 per cent over the past week to 34 per cent, former Labor strategist and pollster Kos Samaras tweeted the campaign was "over". But asked about Mr Samaras' comment, the prime minister said the campaign was not finished. "It’s only done when people cast their ballots," Mr Albanese said. "We'll wait and see when they cast their vote, I'm not getting ahead of the Australian people — I know some arrogance has crept into the No side campaign."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'Not getting ahead': Albanese rejects that Yes vote is sunk

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The latest in our look at the the 2023 draft crop will zoom in on three young footballers tied to the Gold Coast academy, and who are all set to become Suns in November. And they are all serious talents. If he was available to everyone, Jed Walter is the one player in this draft who would give Harley Reid a run for his money as number one pick. Walter is a mobile and skilful key forward, incredibly hard working and excellent in the air. A really complete package at CHF. Then there's Ethan Read, a ruckman who can shift forward if he needs to. Read's draft ranking was already high, but has only been boosted further by an incredible result in the 2km time trial at the draft combine this weekend, where he finished third. Capping off the trio is Jake Rogers, a slick and agile midfielder who lit things up when playing for the AFL Academy side earlier this year. He's rated somewhere around the 10-12 mark in this draft, and is in the top handful of midfield options. All will be Suns next year and beyond. What a haul.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Senate committee examining the Commonwealth Bilateral Air Service Agreements has delivered its final report this afternoon, finding "clear evidence" of the "aggressive use of market power by Qantas" over the federal government's decision to reject additional flights by Qatar Airways. The Senate committee was established last month in response to the federal government's decision to reject a request for Qatar Airways that would see 28 additional weekly flights added to their schedule, with Transport Minister Catherine King saying the decision was made in the "national interest". The committee has made 10 recommendations, including that the competition watchdog reinstate its monitoring of domestic airlines, and the federal government "immediately review" the decision. Committee chair and Nationals Senator Bridget McKenzie said the report contained strong recommendations that would ultimately benefit Australians with cheaper airfares. "At a time of a cost-of-living crisis in Australia the Government has made decisions that have protected Qantas' market share and kept the cost of airfares higher for Australian families and exporters, and they have delayed making critical decisions to improve the reliability of domestic travel especially at Sydney Airport," Senator McKenzie said. "The committee heard evidence that Australians could have been enjoying cheaper flights to Europe and the Middle East as early as April this year had the Government approved additional Qatar Airways flights, and that Turkish Airlines had planned to offer additional flights in time for families to reunite overseas this Christmas. "Clear evidence was provided of the aggressive use of market power by Qantas and the committee has called for reinstatement of Australian Competition and Consumer Commission monitoring of the domestic airline industry and for the competition watchdog to inquire into anti-competitive behaviour in the sector ."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BREAKING: Air services inquiry delivers final report, makes 10 recommendations

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Some government workers with Services Australia will go on strike today, with other Australian Public Service staff planning industrial action over frustrations their salaries are not keeping pace with inflation. Members of the Community and Public Sector Union (CPSU) will strike for 24 hours from today seeking a better pay offer. The union has rejected the federal government's revised pay offer of 11.2% over three years, saying it doesn't match cost-of-living pressures. "There are very real cost-of-living pressures on workers right across the economy, and the public sector is no different, " said CPSU national secretary Melissa Donnelly. "The Albanese Labor government can and should do better on pay for its own workforce." Ms Donnelly said she expects the strike will impact services like Centrelink. "It is unfortunately likely to have some impact on services across the Services Australia network ," she said. "Be it customers contacting the smart centres, that is the call centres, or people attending in face in service centres." Services Australia is encouraging those who need to access their services and can't delay while the strike is taking place to use self-service: For more about the Services Australia strike, you can read the below analysis from the ABC's Markus Mannheim — he's taken a look at employment data and to try and assess just how much public servants are actually worth.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australian gold stocks have jumped by as much as 5% today, which is their biggest intraday percentage gain since July 13. It follows strong gold bullion prices and has seen Australian gold prices pushing higher for a second straight trading session. It's also prompted strong performances by gold miners on the market, with Newcrest Mining up by as much as 4.9% — its biggest intraday gain since April 11. Northern Star Resources is also reaping the benefits, climbing by 5.9% for its biggest same-day gain since July 13.
